g" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"__wf_reserved_inherit" width=3D"auto" height=3D"=
auto" id=3D""></div><figcaption id=3D""><a href=3D"https://gaussian37.githu=
b.io/dl-concept-quantization/">Fig 4.</a> An example of quantization from 3=
2-bit float to 8-bit integer.</figcaption></figure><p id=3D"">=E2=80=8D</p>=
<h1 id=3D"">How mixed precision speeds up AI inferences</h1><p id=3D""><a h=
ref=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.com/modes/train/#train-settings">Mixed prec=
ision</a> is a technique that uses different numerical precisions for vario=
us parts of a <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/perceptrons-and-n=
eural-networks-basic-principles-of-computer-vision">neural network</a>. By =
combining higher precision values, such as 32-bit floats, with lower-precis=
ion values, like 16-bit or 8-bit floats, mixed precision makes it possible =
for <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/a-history-of-vision-models"=
>computer vision models </a>to accelerate training and reduce memory usage =
without sacrificing accuracy.</p><p id=3D"">During training, mixed precisio=
n is achieved by using lower precision in specific layers while keeping hig=
her precision where needed across the network. This is done through casting=
 and loss scaling. Casting converts data types between different precisions=
 as required by the model. Loss scaling adjusts the reduced precision to pr=
event numerical underflow, ensuring stable training. Mixed precision is esp=
ecially useful for large models and large batch sizes. </p><figure id=3D"" =
class=3D"w-richtext-figure-type-image w-richtext-align-fullwidth" style=3D"=
max-width:1348px" data-rt-type=3D"image" data-rt-align=3D"fullwidth" data-r=
t-max-width=3D"1348px"><div id=3D""><img src=3D"https://cdn.prod.website-fi=
les.com/680a070c3b99253410dd3df5/69e1fe09414fea790c84cefe_680a070c3b9925341=
0dd46dd_67ed557668ef26d8645abb10_6737388d606474b3fdf8d5fe_6737386afdab012f8=
5363071_Guide_fig5.png" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"__wf_reserved_inherit" widt=
h=3D"auto" height=3D"auto" id=3D""></div><figcaption id=3D""><a href=3D"htt=
ps://docs.ultralytics.com/guides/model-training-tips/#mixed-precision-train=
ing">Fig 5.</a> Mixed precision training uses both 16-bit (FP16) and 32-bit=
 (FP32) floating-point types.</figcaption></figure><p id=3D"">=E2=80=8D</p>=
<h1 id=3D"">Balancing model accuracy and efficiency</h1><p id=3D"">Now that=
 we've covered several model optimization techniques, let=E2=80=99s discuss=
 how to decide which one to use based on your specific needs. The choice de=
pends on factors like the available <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/=
blog/running-ultralytics-yolo-models-on-intels-ai-pc-with-openvino">hardwar=
e</a>, the computational and memory constraints of the <a href=3D"https://d=
ocs.ultralytics.com/modes/export/">deployment environment,</a> and the requ=
ired level of accuracy.&nbsp;</p><p id=3D"">For instance, smaller, faster m=
odels are better suited for mobile devices with limited resources, while la=
rger, more accurate models can be used on high-performance systems. Here=E2=
=80=99s how each technique aligns with <a href=3D"https://docs.ultralytics.=
com/guides/defining-project-goals/">different goals</a>:</p><ul id=3D""><li=
 id=3D""><strong id=3D"">Pruning:</strong> It is ideal for reducing model s=
ize without significantly impacting accuracy, making it perfect for resourc=
e-constrained devices like mobile phones or Internet of Things (IoT) device=
s.<br>=E2=80=8D</li><li id=3D""><strong id=3D"">Quantization</strong>: A gr=
eat option for shrinking model size and speeding up <a href=3D"https://www.=
ultralytics.com/blog/how-to-use-ultralytics-yolo11-for-image-classification=
">inference</a>, particularly on mobile devices and <a href=3D"https://www.=
ultralytics.com/blog/show-and-tell-yolov8-deployment-on-embedded-devices">e=
mbedded systems</a> with limited memory and processing power. It works well=
 for applications where slight accuracy reductions are acceptable.<br>=E2=
=80=8D</li><li id=3D""><strong id=3D"">Mixed precision</strong>: Designed f=
or large-scale models, this technique reduces memory usage and accelerates =
training on hardware like GPUs and <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/g=
lossary/tpu-tensor-processing-unit">TPUs</a> that support mixed-precision o=
perations. It is often used in high-performance tasks where efficiency matt=
ers.<br>=E2=80=8D</li><li id=3D""><strong id=3D"">Hyperparameter tuning</st=
rong>: While computationally intensive, it=E2=80=99s essential for applicat=
ions that require high accuracy, such as <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics=
.com/blog/using-yolo11-for-tumor-detection-in-medical-imaging">medical imag=
ing</a> or <a href=3D"https://www.ultralytics.com/blog/ai-in-self-driving-c=
ars">autonomous driving</a>.</li></ul></div><div id=3D"key-takeaways" style=
=3D"scroll-margin-top: 10rem;"><h2 id=3D"">Key takeaways</h2><p id=3D"">Mod=
el optimization is a vital part of machine learning, especially for deployi=
ng AI in real-world applications. Techniques like hyperparameter tuning, mo=
del pruning, quantization, and mixed precision help improve the performance=
, efficiency, and resource use of computer vision models. These optimizatio=
ns make models faster and less resource-intensive, which is ideal for devic=
es with limited memory and processing power. Optimized models are also easi=
er to scale and deploy across different platforms, enabling AI solutions th=
at are both effective and adaptable to a wide range of uses.</p><p id=3D"">=
